TY  - JOUR
AU  - Golez, Benjamin
T1  - Expected Returns and Dividend Growth Rates Implied by Derivative Markets
PY  - 2014
Y1  - 2014/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hht131
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 27
IS  - 3
SP  - 790
EP  - 822
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - The dividend-price ratio is a noisy proxy for expected returns when expected dividend growth is time-varying. This paper uses a new and forward-looking measure of dividend growth extracted from S&amp;P 500 futures and options to correct the dividend-price ratio for changes in expected dividend growth. Over January 1994 through June 2011, dividend growth implied by derivative markets reliably forecasts future dividend growth, and the corrected dividend-price ratio predicts S&amp;P 500 returns substantially better than the standard dividend-price ratio, in-sample and out-of-sample. Time-varying expected dividend growth is important to explain price movements, especially because it is highly correlated with expected returns.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hht131
ER  - 



